Bulkification

What: Writing Apex so a single invocation correctly handles a collection of records rather than one. Triggers receive up to 200 records per invocation; a bulkified trigger processes all 200 with a fixed number of queries and DML statements regardless of batch size.

Why it matters: Salesforce is multi-tenant, so governor limits are hard per-transaction ceilings — 100 SOQL, 150 DML statements, 50,000 rows retrieved, 10s CPU, 6 MB heap. Exceeding them throws System.LimitException, which is uncatchable and rolls back the entire transaction. Non-bulkified code works perfectly for a single record from a UI edit and dies the first time someone runs a Data Loader import or a Flow does a mass update. That's a production bug that never appeared in testing.

The shape: collect → query once → map → iterate.

apex
// collect keys
Set<Id> accountIds = new Set<Id>();
for (Opportunity o : opps) {
    if (o.AccountId != null) accountIds.add(o.AccountId);
}
if (accountIds.isEmpty()) return;

// one query
Map<Id, Account> accounts = new Map<Id, Account>([
    SELECT Id, AnnualRevenue FROM Account WHERE Id IN :accountIds
]);

// O(1) lookups, DML collected outside the loop
List<Task> toInsert = new List<Task>();
for (Opportunity o : opps) {
    Account a = accounts.get(o.AccountId);
    if (a != null && a.AnnualRevenue > 10000000) {
        toInsert.add(new Task(WhatId = o.Id, Subject = 'Enterprise review'));
    }
}
if (!toInsert.isEmpty()) insert toInsert;

The trap most people miss: it isn't only about loops. Nested loops over two collections blow the CPU limit without a single query inside them. And a Map isn't optional decoration — it's what turns an O(n²) scan into O(n).

