Recursive trigger prevention

Where recursion comes from: DML in an after trigger on the same object; workflow field updates re-firing update triggers; flows updating the record they were triggered by; roll-up summaries putting the parent through its own full save procedure; two objects' triggers updating each other.

The ceiling: Maximum trigger depth exceeded at 16 levels — uncatchable, full rollback. But that's the lucky failure. The common one is recursing twice, creating a duplicate child record or double-incrementing a counter, with no exception at all.

Three approaches, in order of preference:

1. Move it to before. If you're setting a field on the record being saved, do it in before with a bare assignment. No DML, no recursion, problem eliminated. This solves the majority of cases.

2. Make the logic idempotent. Gate on an actual field change:

apex
Set<Id> renamed = new Set<Id>();
for (Account a : Trigger.new) {
    if (a.Name != Trigger.oldMap.get(a.Id).Name) renamed.add(a.Id);
}
if (renamed.isEmpty()) return;   // recursive pass exits here naturally

On the second pass Trigger.old holds what the first pass wrote, so nothing looks changed and the set comes back empty. No static state to manage.

3. A static guard, when you genuinely need cross-invocation state. Statics live for the execution context, which is the right scope — but scope it to records, not to a boolean:

apex
public class RecursionGuard {
    private static Map<String, Set<Id>> processed = new Map<String, Set<Id>>();

    public static Set<Id> claim(String key, Set<Id> candidates) {
        if (!processed.containsKey(key)) processed.put(key, new Set<Id>());
        Set<Id> seen = processed.get(key);
        Set<Id> fresh = new Set<Id>(candidates);
        fresh.removeAll(seen);
        seen.addAll(fresh);
        return fresh;
    }
}

The trap: public static Boolean hasRun = false is the answer everyone gives and it's broken. DML over 200 records fires the trigger in chunks of 200 — separate, legitimate invocations. Chunk 1 sets the flag; chunks 2 and 3 silently skip. Update 450 records, process 200, drop 250. Passes every test that inserts fewer than 201 records. Saying this in an interview is what distinguishes you from someone who read a blog post.

Also worth knowing: statics reset between each Batch Apex execute() call, so a guard behaves differently in batch than in a single transaction.

