Trigger handler pattern

What: Keep the trigger file as a two-line dispatcher and put all logic in Apex classes.

apex
trigger AccountTrigger on Account (before insert, before update, after insert, after update) {
    new AccountTriggerHandler().run();
}

Why:

One trigger per object is mandatory because execution order across multiple triggers on the same object is undefined. A handler makes that constraint livable instead of producing a 900-line file.
Testability. Trigger bodies can't be unit tested in isolation — you need DML to invoke them. Service methods taking plain List<sObject> can be called directly with in-memory records, no database round trip.
Recursion control has somewhere to live. A guard in a trigger body isn't testable; in a class it is.
Bypass capability. Data migrations and test setup need to skip automation.

The layering that matters:

AccountTrigger.trigger     dispatch only
  └─ AccountTriggerHandler routes by Trigger.operationType, holds the casts
       └─ AccountService   static methods, plain collections, business logic

The handler knows about trigger context; the service doesn't. That split is the whole point — it's what makes the logic callable from a Queueable, a Flow-invocable method, or a test without any of them pretending to be a trigger.

Base class dispatch:

apex
public void run() {
    if (isBypassed(handlerName)) return;
    switch on Trigger.operationType {
        when BEFORE_INSERT { this.beforeInsert(); }
        when BEFORE_UPDATE { this.beforeUpdate(); }
        when AFTER_INSERT  { this.afterInsert();  }
        // ...
    }
}

with protected virtual no-op methods the concrete handler overrides selectively.

The trap: register all seven events in the trigger file even if unused. Adding an event later means editing the trigger, which means a deployment touching a trigger; registering upfront means you only ever touch Apex classes.

If you're prepping these as interview answers, the follow-up questions you should expect are: "how would you test that?" (201+ records to prove chunking safety), "what's the order of execution?" (you've got that), and "when would you use a flow instead of a trigger?" — before-save flows are roughly 10× faster for simple same-record field updates, so the modern split is declarative field updates in flow, complex logic and callouts in Apex.
